title.narrative: STATUTORY SERVICE PROVIDERS HAVE INCREASED AUTHORITY..

description.narrative: Statutory service providers have increased authority, resources and knowledge to provide quality child protection services to the most vulnerable boys and girls in Afghanistan, which contributes to Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: CHILD PROTECTION outcome: Girls and boys vulnerable and exposed to violence, abuse and exploitation are better protected by institutional (formal and informal) and legislative frameworks which include services and systems.

title.narrative: Statutory service providers have increased authority, resources and knowledge to provide quality child protection services to themost vulnerable boys and girls in Afghanistan

description.narrative: 5,567 statutory service providers including health and law enforcement officials, have increased knowledge and skills to provide quality case management to a total of 19,570 (13,474boys: 6,096) and preventive and responsive child protection services to more than 1,003,704 individuals including 838,793children (Boys: 475,339 & Girls:363,454)including 307,907 children have their births registered. Cash plus support benefited2,765households in 5 regions for 3 months, which mitigated child protection risks and supported children to access other services including health, education, and birth registration. Despite the collapse of the welfare system, UNICEF stayed and delivered through NGOs and direct implementation | Status:On-track | As-of Date:12/01/2022
